<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1875-01-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1875-01-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="284" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d284">
                    <head>No. 280.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">Edward
                                Thornton</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1875-01-23"><hi rend="italic">January</hi> 23, 1875</date>.
                            (Received January 25.)</dateline></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                        your note of yesterday’s date, informing me of the views of the Government
                        of the United States relative to the extent of maritime jurisdiction which
                        can properly be claimed by any power.</p>
                    <p>In thanking you for your note, I beg to say that I shall forward a copy of it
                        to the Earl of Derby by the first opportunity.</p>
                    <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>EDW’D THORNTON.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>